SIMPLE: permutation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Permutation
<hw>Per`mu*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r`m⟦usl⟧"t⟦amac⟧"sn⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>permutatio</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>permutation</ets>. See <er>Permute</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of permuting; exchange of the thing for another; mutual
transference; interchange.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The violent convulsions and <qex>permutations</qex> that have been
made in property.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The arrangement of
any determinate number of things, as units, objects, letters, etc., in
all possible orders, one after the other; -- called also
<altname>alternation</altname>. Cf. <er>Combination</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
4.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any one of such possible
arrangements.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Barter; exchange.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Permutation lock</b></col>, <cd>a lock in which the parts
can be transposed or shifted, so as to require different arrangements of
the tumblers on different occasions of unlocking.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1069 --></p>

<p><ent>Permute</ent>⟦br⟧
